                                        2326
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "Two (not necessarily finite- dimensional) subspaces of a vector space are called adjacent if their intersection is a hyperplane in each of these subspaces. Any two adjacent subspaces are of the same dimension and codimension. Classic Chow's theorem 2 characterizes semilinear automorphisms of vector spaces over division rings as adjacency preserving transformations of Grassmannians formed by finitedimensional subspaces. This result is a generalization of the Fundamental Theorem of Projective Geometry characterizing semilinear automorphisms as automorphisms of projective spaces. There are analogues of Chow's theorem for totally isotropic subspaces of sesquilinear forms, singular subspaces of quadratic forms and various types of matrix spaces 3 16 24. An extension of Chow's theorem on Grassmannians consisting of subspaces with infinite dimension and codimension is an open problem. We refer to 17 Section 2.4] for an explanation why this problem is hard."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
